VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'People have been promising cursor for video for 2 years. A magic editor where you just talk to an AI and it cuts your footage for you. And every single time it has been a gorgeous demo that falls apart the'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'second you actually touch it. Then yesterday a Y Combinator startup shipped one. For free, open source. And it does one thing none of the others'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'did. So I spent today taking it completely apart to answer the only question that matters. Is Palmier Pro the real thing? Or is it just a prettier demo?'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Let me give you the honest version. Palmier Pro launched on June 17th from a tiny two-person team, Marcos Rico Peng and his co-founder Harrison out of Y Combinator.'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And the first surprise is what it is not. It is not a website. It is not a clunky browser wrapper pretending to be an app. It is a real native Mac editor written'

[01:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from scratch in Swift that looks and behaves like Premiere or CapCut. You download it with no login and you can just edit video like a normal person.'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'That part is genuinely free and fully open source. No catch, no trial. But here is the twist that makes everyone pay attention. The moment you open Palmier it quietly starts a tiny server'

[01:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'running on your own computer. You will never see it. It just sits there at a local address waiting. And that little server is the entire reason this thing matters'

[01:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because of what is allowed to connect to it. To see why that is a big deal, look at how every other AI video tool works. They are vending machines. You type a prompt,'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the machine thinks for a minute, and it spits out a finished clip and hands it back to you. You cannot really get inside it. You cannot nudge one cut or move one clip without starting the whole thing over.'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Palmyra flipped that completely. That server it opened speaks a standard called MCP, the same plug that powers Claude\'s tools. And Claude code, Claude desktop, Cursor or Codex'

[02:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can connect straight into it. Now, the AI is not generating in some separate tab far away from your work. It is reading the exact timeline you are staring at and editing it directly.'

[02:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Trimming a clip, splitting a take, reordering your shots, dropping new footage into the gap. This is the precise trick that made Cursor win'

[02:52] [scene:talk]
